Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Preheat your #grill{} to its highest setting. Trim the
@green beans{80%g} and chop into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated)
(or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped).
Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(halved and deseeded), deseed then finely chop.

Fill a large #saucepan{} with boiling water from the kettle. Bring back to the boil
with a @salt{0.25%tsp} and half the @ground turmeric{1/2%tsp}. When boiling,
add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Drain in a
#sieve{}.

Pop the @British chicken breasts{2} onto your #chopping board{} and cut into the
flesh widthways at 1cm intervals. Be careful not to cut all the way through!

> See pic in the original recipe for guidance on hasselback cuts.

In a #bowl{} mix the @tandoori masala spice{1%tsp}, the remaining @ground turmeric{1/2%tsp}
and half of the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g}. Add the chicken and season with
@salt{}. Use your hands to coat the chicken. Transfer to a piece of #foil{} and pop
onto a #baking tray{} or a #grill pan{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Pop the chicken under the grill and cook until scorched, ~{5%minutes}. Turn and
repeat on the other side, another ~{5%minutes}. Lower the heat and cook until
the chicken is cooked through, another ~{2%minutes} each side.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the chicken cooks, heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} over medium
heat. When hot, add the green beans and stir fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Add the garlic, cook for ~{1%minute} more and then stir in the cooked, drained
rice. Season to taste with @salt{}. Mix in half the coriander and chilli.

Mix the rest of the coriander and chilli through the remaining @low fat natural
yoghurt{75%g}. Share the rice between your plates and serve the tandoori chicken
alongside. Finish with a drizzle of the yoghurt and enjoy!